<h2>I. A 100K Upvote Question on Zhihu</h2>

<p>If we ask what's been steadily depreciating in 2025, one answer commands consensus: <strong>money.</strong></p>

<p>Not because inflation is out of control, but because of a more fundamental shift — as AGI's battlefield extends from code to creativity, from customer service to consulting, from translation to content creation, more and more people are reacting not with fear, but by asking themselves one big question:</p>

<p><strong>"If money were no longer an issue, what would I most want to do?"</strong></p>

<p>The popularity of this question is a social signal. It tells us two things are happening simultaneously:</p>

<p>First, many people have realized that the "way to earn money" in the AI era is being fundamentally restructured — the old "sell your time for income" model is collapsing.</p>

<p>Second, as the urgency of "how to survive" fades, the existential question of "why live" emerges from behind it.</p>

<p><strong>This is not a chicken-soup-for-the-soul question. It is a collective inquiry taking shape in real time — because AI is gradually erasing "survival anxiety" from most people's agendas, pushing "meaning anxiety" to the front.</strong></p>

<h2>II. The Most Popular 'Waste Life' Answers Reveal a Trap</h2>

<p>Scrolling through the responses to this question, I found the most upvoted answers clustered tightly: <strong>"travel the world" and "lie on the couch doing nothing"</strong> — "see the Northern Lights in Norway," "grow vegetables and keep cats in the countryside," "watch the ocean and binge shows every day."</p>

<p>These answers feel warm. But look closer and they all point to the same pattern: <strong>consumption disguised as fulfillment.</strong></p>

<p>Here's the critical question: <strong>If money really stopped being a concern tomorrow, what would actually happen?</strong></p>

<p>People answering this assume "I can finally do what I love." But human psychology has a counterintuitive feature — <strong>when survival goals disappear, self-created goals don't automatically appear.</strong></p>

<p>Harvard psychologist Daniel Gilbert's research on lottery winners revealed an unsettling finding: most big winners returned to their baseline happiness within two years. Not because money doesn't matter, but because <strong>a life without goals is more hollow than a life of exhaustion.</strong></p>

<p>"I want to travel the world" — great, and after you've traveled it?<br>"I want to watch the ocean every day" — how long until it gets boring?</p>

<p><strong>This isn't about mocking these answers. It's about pointing out that when we say "waste my life on X," our brain defaults to the "escape" circuit, not the "creation" circuit.</strong></p>

<h2>III. The Twist — AI Actually Makes 'Wasting Life on What You Love' Possible</h2>

<p>Here's the paradoxical but accurate observation:</p>

<p><strong>The more "money-no-object" the era becomes, the more you need the ability to define your own value.</strong></p>

<p>For the past 20 years, "worrying about money" has been a constraint for most people. It forced you to get up every morning with something to do. AI is now loosening that constraint: AI writes your code, polishes your articles, generates your designs, runs your analysis.</p>

<p><strong>The moment that constraint lifts is the real test — what do you actually care about?</strong></p>

<p>You think you could "waste" your life gardening. Great — have AI design your smart garden system, automate maintenance. Then what?<br>You think you could "waste" your life teaching writing. Great — have AI set homework, grade assignments. Then what?</p>

<p><strong>AI can remove the "make a living" middleman. It cannot remove the "why are we doing this" question.</strong></p>

<h2>IV. Redefining 'Waste' — From Time-Killing to Value Creation</h2>

<p>A more productive way to frame this: shift the meaning of "waste" from "killing time" to <strong>"pure investment without mechanical returns."</strong></p>

<p>The difference between a "creator" and a "consumer" isn't the type of activity. It's that <strong>the creator turns "waste" into "leaving something behind."</strong></p>

<p>Want to garden? Not to kill time, but to cultivate a community garden that brings color and life to passersby.<br>Want to teach? Not for the hourly rate, but to see a student shift from "I can't" to "I'll try."<br>Want to write a novel? Not for ad revenue, but for a perspective that only you can capture.</p>

<p><strong>The biggest opportunity of the AI era: "wasting your life on what you love" is no longer a fantasy — it's a viable strategy.</strong></p>

<p>— As long as what you "waste" turns into something others want to engage with or use.</p>

<h2>V. Three Specific Ways to 'Waste' Your Life</h2>

<h3>Move One: Use AI for a "free" micro-service</h3>
<p>You love translating poetry. Nobody pays for it. Now AI does the first pass, and your human taste does the final polish. Near-zero cost. One post a week on a newsletter. Build 1,000 readers who love translated poetry. It doesn't earn money — but it creates value.</p>

<h3>Move Two: Use AI to build your own niche learning community</h3>
<p>You're obsessed with a specific topic (Viking history, moss taxonomy, baroque music). Use AI to organize research, generate course outlines, design interactive exercises. Start a Discord with 20 like-minded people. No fees. Deep participation.</p>

<h3>Move Three: Turn your craft into a free product</h3>
<p>You do pottery, restore old books, identify birds by song. Use AI to record your process, write tutorials, build interactive tools. Put it online. No paywalls.</p>

<p><strong>What these three moves share: none of them are "for money." But all of them create some form of public value. And that value will likely, at some unexpected moment and in some unexpected form — including money — find its way back to you.</strong></p>

<h2>VI. So, What Is the Real Answer?</h2>

<p>I don't have a single answer. But I do have a test:</p>

<p><strong>When you no longer need work to prove you are "useful" — what would you still do?</strong></p>

<p>If the answer is something you'd still do even if nobody paid you, nobody liked it, nobody knew who you were — that thing is what you should "waste" your life on.</p>

<p>And the meaning of AI in this context: <strong>for the first time, it makes it possible to scale these "unprofitable" passions.</strong></p>

<p>Gardening isn't just gardening — it's a gardening content system.<br>Reading poetry isn't just poetry — it's a sustained commentary project.<br>Teaching kids isn't just teaching — it's an AI-assisted learning design lab.</p>

<p><strong>There is no longer such a thing as "hobby vs. survival."</strong></p>

<p><strong>Because AI has built the bridge between them. You just have to decide if you truly want to cross it.</strong></p>

